**Yes, Zauq signs his name in the maqta.** The final couplet (paragraph `p-0786bf`, chapter 16) reads:

> *Woh dil ke jiss mein soz-e-mohabbat na hove **'Zauq'***  
> *Behtar hai sang uss se ke uss mein sharar toh hai*

("That heart in which there is no ardor of love, O Zauq, / A stone is better than it — for at least a stone has a spark.")

The takhallus `ذوقؔ` (Zauq) appears in the first hemistich of the maqta, in the standard classical position, addressed to the poet himself.
